In the James S. Brady Press Briefing Room, White House Deputy Press Secretary Karine Jean-Pierre provided updates on various topics. She discussed the designation of three historic sites as part of a new national monument to honor the legacy of Emmett Till and Mamie Till-Mobley. She also highlighted President Biden's focus on tackling the mental health crisis and announced a landmark proposed rule to ensure equal access to mental health care. Jean-Pierre mentioned positive economic indicators, such as high consumer confidence and a surge in new business applications. She also announced a new security assistance package to support Ukraine in defending against Russian attacks. During the Q&A session, Jean-Pierre addressed questions about Americans freelancing to fight in Ukraine, Hunter Biden's court appearance, the President's relationship with Prime Minister Netanyahu, the use of legacy admissions in education, and the President's views on systemic racism. She also commented on the President's meeting with Emmett Till's cousin and the disappearance of China's foreign minister.